[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
2NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "5c76b42c76112484974b1da515b3cc8811fce284bf9cdf08ec32708336ec7d6e"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/entry_management"]
[Student "S"]
{East is to play 3NT. South leads the \C3, North plays the \CA.

Winners:   \S=1  \H=2  \D=1  \C=2  Total = 6

You have the possibility of one additional \S winner if South holds the \SK. However, \Ds is your best suit and if North holds the \DK you could gain all three winners that you need from that suit. But of course you need perhaps 2 dummy entries. Do you have them?

Well, you probably do. South's small \C lead probably indicates an honor, and with North playing the \CA you can be pretty sure that South holds the \CJ. So by playing your \CK underneath the \CA you set up a second entry to dummy via the \C finesse.

Assume North now plays a \H. Take your \HA and play a \C to dummy's \CT. Lead a \D and finesse the \DJ, which holds. Play another \C to dummy and finesse another \D. Now play your \DA and smile when the \DK drops and your fourth \D becomes a winner.

As soon as North put up the \CA you knew you could win 2 \C tricks.

By unblocking the \CK you were still pretty confident that you would get the two tricks, but the bonus was in the extra dummy entry your unblock created.}
[Play "W"]C3

